\hline
9.8 & 98k & 29.9k & 9.8 & 9.8\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:org4263f5d}
\subsection{Unstabilized common emitter}
\label{sec:org4c61004}
Initially, a 4M\(\Omega\) resistor was used for R\(_{\text{B}}\), however, this was found to produce an I\(_{\text{C}}\) far below 1mA, so it was exchanged for a 3M\(\Omega\) resistor. This was probably because the actual \(\beta\) of the transistor was below our estimated value of 400. Now, I\(_{\text{C}}\) was measured to be 1.2mA. Similarly, this explains the discrepancy between the calculated and the mesaured value of the input resistance. Cooling the device using a cooling spray reduced the gain of this configuration to 80 from 187. V\(_{\text{T}}\) is reduced with temperature so looking at the equation for A\(_{\text{V}}\) you might expect the gain to increase, however, in this unstabilized configuration, I\(_{\text{C}}\) is highly dependent on \(\beta\), which is highly dependent on temperature. Cooling the device greatly reduces \(\beta\) and hence I\(_{\text{C}}\) and V\(_{\text{Rc}}\), which explains the reduction in gain.\newline\newline
Knowing these relationships, we can also say that we could increase the gain of this amplifier by either using a transistor with a higher \(\beta\) value or keeping the device at a higher temperature. 
